<font color="#FF0000">IN MEMORY OF A SOLDIERS MOTHER</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec 22 19:02:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I received a Christmas card today from the daughter of Mrs. VanDeWalle, whose son Greg is mentioned above,<br><br>
REUNION &amp; REFLECTION<br>
Wed Aug 13 13:34:12 US/Eastern 1997 <br><br>
And above in response to Regina<br><br>
IN HONOR OF A FALLEN COMRADE<br>
Thu Dec 18 19:40:40 US/Eastern 1997 <br><br>
In the above post a poem Greg wrote is posted as well as a note referring to Mrs. Van De Walle,<br>
“Some time after his death, a war protester  ….. called Ms. Van De Walle and informed her that they were going to read out loud his name in protest as having died in vain in Vietnam.<br><br>
Ms. Van De Walle marched into the midst of the protesters group and said, <br>
&quot;You will not dishonor my sons name, he did not die in vain, he died for what he believed in and was proud to be a Marine. They never spoke his name that day. “<br><br>
The card I received to day read:<br><br>
“Cookie,<br>
Enclosed is a memorial card from mom’s funeral service. Two days before Thanksgiving we though she had a stroke, but it turned out to be a form of encephalitis. <br><br>
She seemed to be on the slow road to recovery, but on Wednesday, December 10 she very suddenly, to the doctor’s surprise also, succumbed. I know she’s in her heavenly home now along with Greg and my dad. <br><br>
She so much enjoyed meeting all you guys at the reunion here in San Antonio. God Bless you and your family.<br><br>
Virginia”<br><br>
When I met Mrs. Van De Walle, last August, there was so much warmth and love in her eyes for all of us that knew her son and who had gathered at the park named after her son to honor him, that we all adopted her as our own mom and she adopted us all as her sons. <br><br>
I remember seeing how tightly she held onto Marty’s hands at the park during the memorial service to Greg. Marty had been right alongside of Greg when he was killed. <br><br>
She was so glad to finally meet Marines who knew and had served in the same unit with her son, and I was so glad to have met her. <br><br>
I know that there must be thousands of other mothers, fathers, spouses, friends, brothers and sisters who lost a loved one in Vietnam that would welcome a correspondence from us who knew their loved ones. I know that while we were all apprehensive about meeting, it turned out to be a very memorable time for all of us. It was well worth the time and the memories.<br><br>
May God Bless her and her family, she was a true patriot, an American and proud mother of a United States Marine who died in Battle.<br><br>

